    public class customPath
extends java.util.ArrayList<com.arcrobotics.ftclib.purepursuit.Waypoint>
    This class represents a pure pursuit path. It is used to store a path's waypoints, and do all the calculation required to traverse the path. A path can be implemented in two different way. The first way is running the loop/updating motor powers manually. This is a good implementation for those teams who wish to just use the pure pursuit section FtcLib and not much else. The other implementation is using the automatic feature. This features does all the hard work for you. Teams who use FtcLib's features to power most of their code will find this method appealing.

    To learn how to implement a pure pursuit path, please see the example implementations and tutorials.

    Version:
    1.3
    Author:
    Michael Baljet, Team 14470

      • init

        public void init()
        Initiates the path. This must be ran before using the path. This checks to make sure everything in the path is valid. Use isLegalPath() to check if a path is valid.

        In order for a path to be considered legal it must have: - At least 2 waypoints. - Begin with a StartWaypoint - End with an EndWaypoint - Not contain any StartWaypoints or EndWaypoints in it's body.

        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalStateException - If the path is not legal.

      • followPath

        public boolean followPath​(com.arcrobotics.ftclib.drivebase.MecanumDrive mecanumDrive,
                          com.arcrobotics.ftclib.command.OdometrySubsystem odometry)
        Initiates the automatic path following feature. The robot will follow the path and perform actions as configured.
        Parameters:
        mecanumDrive - The robot's drive base. Only mecanum drives are supported currently.
        odometry - The robot's odometry.
        Returns:
        True if the path completed successfully, false if the path did not (timed out, lost path, etc.).
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalStateException - If automatic mode is disabled/not configured or the init has not been ran.

      • loop

        public double[] loop​(double vPosition,
                     double hPosition,
                     double rotation)
        This is the principle path method. After everything is configured and initiated, this method can be used. Using the robot's horizontal, y, and rotation, this method calculates the appropriate motor powers for the robot to follow the path. This method calls all triggered/interrupted actions automatically. If this returns zero motor speeds {0, 0, 0} that means the path has either (1) timed out, (2) lost the path and retrace was disabled, or (3) reached the destination. Use isFinished() and timedOut() to troubleshoot.
        Parameters:
        vPosition - Robot's current vertical position.
        hPosition - Robot's current horizontal position.
        rotation - Robot's current rotation.
        Returns:
        A double array containing the motor powers. a[0] is the x power, a[1] is the y power, and a[2] is the turn power.
